<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Just an addendum to previous posts, I have found it to be much cheaper to switch to higher metals and lower gems once the next stone in line costs more than the metal. For example, I started in silver which cost me 5gp per bar and worked my way to trivial in jade.  At this point, I found it cheaper to switch to electrum and malachite than silver and pearl.  By the time I was trivial with that combo, my skill was 74 and all silver items were also trivial.<br>
  Also, it seems pointless to enchant the metal first when training unless using a useful combination.  Magical jewelry brings no higher price from the vendors than unenchanted.  Most of the time, you are using metal/gem combos with stats that no one will buy.  I cannot see anyone paying cost for an electrum or gold piece that is strictly a resistance buff which is what you make with lesser stones.<br>
  But to answer the original question, yes you most certainly can fail on trivial items.  However, I have noticed that once your skill is at least 15 points higher than trivial, your success rate will be 95-97% or close to that. Intelligence buffs help greatly when practicing for skill, but skill level is the primary determining factor on successes, not wisdom- especially on trivial items.  My skill is currently 163 (very expensive at this stage) and I have used this method my entire training period.  I am currently trivial up to gold/onyx and it costs approx 11pp 5gp per attempt now with skill gains approx 1 per 10 attempts at 156 int.<p>

 Colour Fluks<br>
 23 Enchanter<br>
 Storm Wolf Guild<br>
 Bertoxx server</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
